This was a profound and powerful introduction to thinkers and community leaders in the Rising Majority/Working Families Party team, and an inspiring reminder to remain vigilant across the intersections of experience, across the globe. Angela Davis and Loan Tran consistently inspired organizers and activists to dispel myopia and paradigms of U.S./American exceptionalism, as well as nationa states, and in doing so become conscious allies of leaders/activists of social and eco-justice in the Global South (the Global South here, is not necessarily regional, but is a term that can be applied to folks living within Western hegemonic nation states). I was interested to learn about the various organizing groups mentioned by Davis and Klein, as well as the Working Families Party, and believe that a more politically aware and engaged community, threading the local and the global into a tighter circle of interrelation will be a huge part of making us aware of the paths of our connection, and will help the movement to support and to love each other even hemispheres away. Thank you all for your work and energy, and I am glad to have taken part and shared this conversation with several folks. In Kindessâ€”JFK Randhawa

feedback: i've always been an activist. i'm a child of the sixties, and love angela davis, and i love naomi klein. i just attended a meeting on zoom with the mid city l a tenants council last night. i appreciated this call very much, but i also felt that it was very important to not just talk about theories and planning. i really would like to have come away with resources and specific actions to take. i personally am feeling up against the wall, because i haven't been going into the office where i work offering holistic health services, and the social security i get has just been covering my rent. without the money that has been covering all the other things, i'm going to need my social security for those things, but that means i can't pay my rent. i did reach out to a legal  organization that the tenants union recommended, but i felt it was important on this call to have put more specific resources, and specific solutions that people could come away with, and know just what to do. otherwise, it seems like there's this elitist, ongoing, ad nauseam philosophical group of organizers talking about theory and strategy, and a disconnect from the immediacy of the moment, in the field, with people who are needing to know what to do for their next step. i'm just being really honest; it doesn't take away from the appreciation i feel about the zoom call...thank you!

admirable effort to bring coalesce to the progressive community. surely a very steep hill to overcome the oligarchy that is our current political paradigm. i am a strong advocate for substantial social, economic and political change. i am hopeful that wfp can succeed!
All of that said, we need to move beyond messaging about what WFP is to what WFP will do.  Let's take a page from WV Governor candidate, Stephen Smith, and hear from the grass-roots from every region about their struggles and hopes for the future, and let's provide a platform to amplify those hope into tangible programs for change.  
While I appreciate that WFP has had some success in NY and NJ, and, hopefully, soon in PA and MD among other states, we need to learn from the people we hope to represent and build a program that speaks to  and for them.  Continuation of the top down, let me tell you what you need approach is our current problem.
